(1, 'IN1400', '205080K', '2022-04-06', '12:54:52', 'ER diagram', '{\"ops\":[{\"insert\":\"ER Diagram From : Guru 99\"},{\"attributes\":{\"align\":\"center\",\"header\":2},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"align\":\"center\"},\"insert\":{\"video\":\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/QpdhBUYk7Kk?showinfo=0\"}},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"What is ER Diagram?\"},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"ER Diagram\"},{\"insert\":\" stands for Entity Relationship Diagram, also known as ERD is a diagram that displays the relationship of entity sets stored in a database. In other words, ER diagrams help to explain the logical structure of databases. ER diagrams are created based on three basic concepts: entities, attributes and relationships.\\nER Diagrams contain different symbols that use rectangles to represent entities, ovals to define attributes and diamond shapes to represent relationships.\\nAt first look, an ER diagram looks very similar to the flowchart. However, ER Diagram includes many specialized symbols, and its meanings make this model unique. The purpose of ER Diagram is to represent the entity framework infrastructure.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"alt\":\"ER Diagram Examples\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu1.png\"}},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"What is ER Model?\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":2},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"ER Model\"},{\"insert\":\" stands for Entity Relationship Model is a high-level conceptual data model diagram. ER model helps to systematically analyze data requirements to produce a well-designed database. The ER Model represents real-world entities and the relationships between them. Creating an ER Model in DBMS is considered as a best practice before implementing your database.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"color\":\"var(--global-palette-highlight)\",\"background\":\"transparent\",\"link\":\"https://www.guru99.com/er-modeling.html\"},\"insert\":\"ER Modeling\"},{\"insert\":\" helps you to analyze data requirements systematically to produce a well-designed database. So, it is considered a best practice to complete ER modeling before implementing your database.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"History of ER models\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":2},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"ER diagrams are visual tools that are helpful to represent the ER model. Peter Chen proposed ER Diagram in 1971 to create a uniform convention that can be used for relational databases and networks. He aimed to use an ER model as a conceptual modeling approach.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Why use ER Diagrams?\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":2},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Here, are prime reasons for using the ER Diagram\\nHelps you to define terms related to entity relationship modeling\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Provide a preview of how all your tables should connect, what fields are going to be on each table\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Helps to describe entities, attributes, relationships\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"ER diagrams are translatable into relational tables which allows you to build databases quickly\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"ER diagrams can be used by database designers as a blueprint for implementing data in specific software applications\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"The database designer gains a better understanding of the information to be contained in the database with the help of ERP diagram\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"ERD Diagram allows you to communicate with the logical structure of the database to users\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Facts about ER Diagram Model\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":2},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Now in this ERD Diagram Tutorial, let’s check out some interesting facts about ER Diagram Model:\"},{\"insert\":\"\\nER model allows you to draw Database Design\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"It is an easy to use graphical tool for modeling data\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Widely used in Database Design\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"It is a GUI representation of the logical structure of a Database\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"It helps you to identifies the entities which exist in a system and the relationships between those entities\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"ER Diagrams Symbols & Notations\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":2},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Entity Relationship Diagram Symbols & Notations\"},{\"insert\":\" mainly contains three basic symbols which are rectangle, oval and diamond to represent relationships between elements, entities and attributes. There are some sub-elements which are based on main elements in ERD Diagram. ER Diagram is a visual representation of data that describes how data is related to each other using different ERD Symbols and Notations.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Following are the main components and its symbols in ER Diagrams:\"},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Rectangles: \"},{\"insert\":\"This Entity Relationship Diagram symbol represents entity types\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Ellipses : \"},{\"insert\":\"Symbol represent attributes\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Diamonds: \"},{\"insert\":\"This symbol represents relationship types\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Lines: \"},{\"insert\":\"It links attributes to entity types and entity types with other relationship types\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Primary key: \"},{\"insert\":\"attributes are underlined\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Double Ellipses: \"},{\"insert\":\"Represent multi-valued attributes\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"alt\":\"ER Diagram Symbols\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu12.png\"}},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Components of the ER Diagram\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":2},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"This model is based on three basic concepts:\\nEntities\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Attributes\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Relationships\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"ER Diagram Examples\"},{\"insert\":\"\\nFor example, in a University database, we might have entities for Students, Courses, and Lecturers. Students entity can have attributes like Rollno, Name, and DeptID. They might have relationships with Courses and Lecturers.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"alt\":\"Components of the ER Diagram\",\"height\":\"742\",\"width\":\"1084\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu2.png\"}},{\"insert\":\"Components of the ER Diagram\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"WHAT IS ENTITY?\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":2},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"A real-world thing either living or non-living that is easily recognizable and nonrecognizable. It is anything in the enterprise that is to be represented in our database. It may be a physical thing or simply a fact about the enterprise or an event that happens in the real world.\\nAn entity can be place, person, object, event or a concept, which stores data in the database. The characteristics of entities are must have an attribute, and a unique key. Every entity is made up of some ‘attributes’ which represent that entity.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Examples of entities:\"},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Person:\"},{\"insert\":\" Employee, Student, Patient\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Place:\"},{\"insert\":\" Store, Building\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Object:\"},{\"insert\":\" Machine, product, and Car\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Event:\"},{\"insert\":\" Sale, Registration, Renewal\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Concept:\"},{\"insert\":\" Account, Course\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Notation of an Entity\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Entity set:\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":3},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Student\\nAn entity set is a group of similar kind of entities. It may contain entities with attribute sharing similar values. Entities are represented by their properties, which also called attributes. All attributes have their separate values. For example, a student entity may have a name, age, class, as attributes.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"height\":\"167\",\"width\":\"692\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu3.png\"}},{\"attributes\":{\"align\":\"center\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Example of Entities:\"},{\"insert\":\"\\nA university may have some departments. All these departments employ various lecturers and offer several programs.\\nSome courses make up each program. Students register in a particular program and enroll in various courses. A lecturer from the specific department takes each course, and each lecturer teaches a various group of students.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Relationship\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":2},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Relationship is nothing but an association among two or more entities. E.g., Tom works in the Chemistry department.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"height\":\"150\",\"width\":\"718\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu4.png\"}},{\"attributes\":{\"align\":\"center\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Entities take part in relationships. We can often identify relationships with verbs or verb phrases.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"For example:\"},{\"insert\":\"\\nYou are attending this lecture\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"I am giving the lecture\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Just loke entities, we can classify relationships according to relationship-types:\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"A student attends a lecture\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"A lecturer is giving a lecture.\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Weak Entities\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":2},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"A weak entity is a type of entity which doesn’t have its key attribute. It can be identified uniquely by considering the primary key of another entity. For that, weak entity sets need to have participation.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"height\":\"436\",\"width\":\"1465\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu5.png\"}},{\"attributes\":{\"align\":\"center\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"In above ER Diagram examples, “Trans No” is a discriminator within a group of transactions in an ATM.\\nLet’s learn more about a weak entity by comparing it with a Strong Entity\\nStrong Entity SetWeak Entity SetStrong entity set always has a primary key.It does not have enough attributes to build a primary key.It is represented by a rectangle symbol.It is represented by a double rectangle symbol.It contains a Primary key represented by the underline symbol.It contains a Partial Key which is represented by a dashed underline symbol.The member of a strong entity set is called as dominant entity set.The member of a weak entity set called as a subordinate entity set.Primary Key is one of its attributes which helps to identify its member.In a weak entity set, it is a combination of primary key and partial key of the strong entity set.In the ER diagram the relationship between two strong entity set shown by using a diamond symbol.The relationship between one strong and a weak entity set shown by using the double diamond symbol.The connecting line of the strong entity set with the relationship is single.The line connecting the weak entity set for identifying relationship is double.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Attributes\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":2},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"It is a single-valued property of either an entity-type or a relationship-type.\\nFor example, a lecture might have attributes: time, date, duration, place, etc.\\nAn attribute in ER Diagram examples, is represented by an Ellipse\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"height\":\"305\",\"width\":\"379\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu6.png\"}},{\"attributes\":{\"align\":\"center\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Types of AttributesDescription\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Simple attribute\"},{\"insert\":\"Simple attributes can’t be divided any further. For example, a student’s contact number. It is also called an atomic value.\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Composite attribute\"},{\"insert\":\"It is possible to break down composite attribute. For example, a student’s full name may be further divided into first name, second name, and last name.\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Derived attribute\"},{\"insert\":\"This type of attribute does not include in the physical database. However, their values are derived from other attributes present in the database. For example, age should not be stored directly. Instead, it should be derived from the DOB of that employee.\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Multivalued attribute\"},{\"insert\":\"Multivalued attributes can have more than one values. For example, a student can have more than one mobile number, email address, etc.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Cardinality\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":2},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Defines the numerical attributes of the relationship between two entities or entity sets.\\nDifferent types of cardinal relationships are:\\nOne-to-One Relationships\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"One-to-Many Relationships\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"May to One Relationships\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Many-to-Many Relationships\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"height\":\"372\",\"width\":\"602\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu7.png\"}},{\"attributes\":{\"align\":\"center\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"1.One-to-one:\"},{\"insert\":\"\\nOne entity from entity set X can be associated with at most one entity of entity set Y and vice versa.\\nExample: One student can register for numerous courses. However, all those courses have a single line back to that one student.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"height\":\"209\",\"width\":\"690\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu8.png\"}},{\"attributes\":{\"align\":\"center\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"2.One-to-many:\"},{\"insert\":\"\\nOne entity from entity set X can be associated with multiple entities of entity set Y, but an entity from entity set Y can be associated with at least one entity.\\nFor example, one class is consisting of multiple students.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"height\":\"226\",\"width\":\"711\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu9.png\"}},{\"attributes\":{\"align\":\"center\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"3. Many to One\"},{\"insert\":\"\\nMore than one entity from entity set X can be associated with at most one entity of entity set Y. However, an entity from entity set Y may or may not be associated with more than one entity from entity set X.\\nFor example, many students belong to the same class.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"height\":\"167\",\"width\":\"692\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu10.png\"}},{\"attributes\":{\"align\":\"center\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"4. Many to Many:\"},{\"insert\":\"\\nOne entity from X can be associated with more than one entity from Y and vice versa.\\nFor example, Students as a group are associated with multiple faculty members, and faculty members can be associated with multiple students.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"height\":\"232\",\"width\":\"773\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu11.png\"}},{\"attributes\":{\"align\":\"center\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"How to Create an Entity Relationship Diagram (ERD)\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":2},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Now in this ERD Diagram Tutorial, we will learn how to create an ER Diagram. Following are the steps to create an ER Diagram:\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"alt\":\"Steps to Create an ER Diagram\",\"height\":\"78\",\"width\":\"594\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu13.png\"}},{\"insert\":\"Steps to Create an ER Diagram\\nLet’s study them with an Entity Relationship Diagram Example:\\nIn a university, a Student enrolls in Courses. A student must be assigned to at least one or more Courses. Each course is taught by a single Professor. To maintain instruction quality, a Professor can deliver only one course\"},{\"attributes\":{\"code-block\":true},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Step 1) Entity Identification\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":3},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"We have three entities\\nStudent\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Course\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Professor\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"height\":\"143\",\"width\":\"580\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu14.png\"}},{\"attributes\":{\"align\":\"center\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Step 2) Relationship Identification\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":3},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"We have the following two relationships\\nThe student is \"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"assigned\"},{\"insert\":\" a course\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Professor \"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"delivers\"},{\"insert\":\" a course\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"height\":\"158\",\"width\":\"837\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu15.png\"}},{\"attributes\":{\"align\":\"center\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Step 3) Cardinality Identification\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":3},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"For them problem statement we know that,\\nA student can be assigned \"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"multiple\"},{\"insert\":\" courses\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"A Professor can deliver only \"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"one\"},{\"insert\":\" course\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"height\":\"152\",\"width\":\"848\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu16.png\"}},{\"attributes\":{\"align\":\"center\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Step 4) Identify Attributes\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":3},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"You need to study the files, forms, reports, data currently maintained by the organization to identify attributes. You can also conduct interviews with various stakeholders to identify entities. Initially, it’s important to identify the attributes without mapping them to a particular entity.\\nOnce, you have a list of Attributes, you need to map them to the identified entities. Ensure an attribute is to be paired with exactly one entity. If you think an attribute should belong to more than one entity, use a modifier to make it unique.\\nOnce the mapping is done, identify the primary Keys. If a unique key is not readily available, create one.\\nEntityPrimary KeyAttributeStudentStudent_IDStudentNameProfessorEmployee_IDProfessorNameCourseCourse_IDCourseName\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"height\":\"293\",\"width\":\"836\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu17.png\"}},{\"attributes\":{\"align\":\"center\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"For Course Entity, attributes could be Duration, Credits, Assignments, etc. For the sake of ease we have considered just one attribute.\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Step 5) Create the ERD Diagram\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":3},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"A more modern representation of Entity Relationship Diagram Example\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"height\":\"131\",\"width\":\"860\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://www.guru99.com/images/1/100518_0621_ERDiagramTu18.png\"}},{\"attributes\":{\"align\":\"center\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Best Practices for Developing Effective ER Diagrams\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":2},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Here are some best practice or example for Developing Effective ER Diagrams.\\nEliminate any redundant entities or relationships\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"You need to make sure that all your entities and relationships are properly labeled\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"There may be various valid approaches to an ER diagram. You need to make sure that the ER diagram supports all the data you need to store\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"You should assure that each entity only appears a single time in the ER diagram\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Name every relationship, entity, and attribute are represented on your diagram\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"Never connect relationships to each other\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"You should use colors to highlight important portions of the ER diagram\"},{\"attributes\":{\"list\":\"bullet\"},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"}]}'),
(5, 'IS1020', '205080K', '2022-04-16', '12:38:07', 'Scarcity', '{\"ops\":[{\"insert\":\"Scarcity\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":1},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"alt\":\"<resource_carousel.datastructures.RCItem object at 0x7fc40983d5f8>\"},\"insert\":{\"image\":\"https://media.nationalgeographic.org/assets/photos/159/047/77a768e9-eac7-48da-a1ea-43670fdc68bf.jpg\"}},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"color\":\"black\",\"background\":\"transparent\"},\"insert\":\"Scarcity\"},{\"insert\":\" is one of the key concepts of \"},{\"attributes\":{\"color\":\"black\",\"background\":\"transparent\"},\"insert\":\"economics\"},{\"insert\":\". It means that the demand for a good or service is greater than the availability of the good or service. Therefore, scarcity can limit the choices available to the consumers who ultimately make up the \"},{\"attributes\":{\"color\":\"black\",\"background\":\"transparent\"},\"insert\":\"economy\"},{\"insert\":\". Scarcity is important for understanding how goods and services are valued. Things that are scarce, like gold, diamonds, or certain kinds of knowledge, are more valuable for being scarce because sellers of these goods and services can set higher prices. These sellers know that because more people want their good or service than there are goods and services available, they can find buyers at a higher cost.\\nScarcity of goods and services is an important variable for economic models because it can affect the decisions made by consumers. For some people, the scarcity of a good or service means they cannot afford it. The economy of any place is made up of these choices by individuals and companies about what they can produce and afford.\\nThe goods and services of any country are limited, which can lead to scarcity. Countries have different resources available to produce goods and services. These resources can be workers, government and private company investment, or raw materials (like trees or coal). Certain limits of scarcity can be balanced by taking resources from one area and using them somewhere else. Sellers like private companies or governments decide how the available resources are spread out. This is done by trying to strike a balance between what consumers need or want, what the government needs, and what will be an efficient use of resources to maximize profits. Countries also import resources from other countries, and export resources from their own. \\nScarcity can be created on purpose. For example, governments control the printing of money, a valuable good. But, paper, cotton, and labor are all widely available across the world, so the things required to make money are not themselves scarce. If governments print too much money, the value of their money decreases, because it has become less scarce. When the supply of money in an economy is too high, it can lead to \"},{\"attributes\":{\"color\":\"black\",\"background\":\"transparent\"},\"insert\":\"inflation\"},{\"insert\":\". Inflation means the amount of money needed to buy a good or service increases—therefore money becomes less valuable, and the same amount of money can buy less over time than it could in the past. It is therefore in a country’s best interest to keep its paper money supply relatively scarce. However, sometimes inflation can help an economy. When money is less scarce, people can spend more, which triggers a rise in production. Low inflation can help an economy grow.\\n\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Media Credits\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":4},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"The audio, illustrations, photos, and videos are credited beneath the media asset, except for promotional images, which generally link to another page that contains the media credit. The Rights Holder for media is the person or group credited.\"},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Director\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":4},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Tyson Brown, National Geographic Society\"},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Author\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":4},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"National Geographic Society\"},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Production Manager\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":4},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Gina Borgia, National Geographic Society\"},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Program Specialists\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":4},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Sarah Appleton, National Geographic Society\"},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Margot Willis, National Geographic Society\"},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Specialist, Content Production\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":4},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Clint Parks\"},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Producer\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":4},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"André Gabrielli, National Geographic Society\"},{\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Last Updated\"},{\"attributes\":{\"header\":4},\"insert\":\"\\n\"},{\"attributes\":{\"bold\":true},\"insert\":\"Oct. 27, 2020\"},{\"insert\":\"\\n\\nRefLink : https://www.nationalgeographic.org/encyclopedia/scarcity/\\n\"}]}'),
